<article class="article">
  <h2>How FD interest actually works</h2>
  <p>Most online examples use simple annual compounding, but Indian banks credit interest on cumulative fixed deposits <strong>quarterly</strong>. That small detail matters: ₹5 lakh at 7% for 5 years grows to about ₹7.07 lakh with quarterly compounding versus ₹7.01 lakh with annual — a ₹6,000+ difference. This calculator defaults to the quarterly method so the number matches your bank's FD receipt.</p>

  <h2>Formula</h2>
  <div class="formula">A = P × (1 + r/m)<sup>m×t</sup></div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>P</strong> — deposit amount</li>
    <li><strong>r</strong> — annual interest rate (as a decimal)</li>
    <li><strong>m</strong> — compounding frequency per year (4 for banks)</li>
    <li><strong>t</strong> — tenure in years</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>₹5,00,000 at 7% p.a. for 5 years, compounded quarterly: A = 5,00,000 × (1 + 0.07/4)<sup>20</sup> ≈ <strong>₹7,07,389</strong>. Interest earned is about ₹2.07 lakh, and the effective annual yield works out to 7.19% — slightly above the quoted 7% because of quarterly compounding.</p>

  <h2>Getting more from your FDs</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Ladder your deposits.</strong> Split a large sum into FDs maturing in different years — you get liquidity every year and can reinvest at prevailing rates.</li>
    <li><strong>Compare across banks.</strong> Small finance banks often pay 1–1.5% more than large banks and carry the same DICGC insurance up to ₹5 lakh.</li>
    <li><strong>Mind the tax.</strong> Interest is taxed at your slab rate every year even if you receive it only at maturity — factor that into comparisons with other options.</li>
    <li><strong>Senior citizens</strong> should always ask for the senior rate and consider the Senior Citizens' Savings Scheme, which typically pays more than bank FDs.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<script>
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function () {
  var comp = CM.seg('seg-comp');
  function recalc() {
    var p = CM.val('p'), r = CM.val('r') / 100, t = CM.val('n');
    var mFreq = parseFloat(comp.value || 4);
    if (p <= 0 || t <= 0) return;
    var fv = p * Math.pow(1 + r / mFreq, mFreq * t);
    var yield_ = (Math.pow(fv / p, 1 / t) - 1) * 100;

    CM.set('out-fv', CM.inr(fv));
    var w = CM.words(fv);
    CM.set('out-fv-sub', w ? 'about ' + w : '');
    CM.set('out-inv', CM.inr(p));
    CM.set('out-int', CM.inr(fv - p));
    CM.set('out-yield', CM.num(yield_, 2) + '%');

    var labels = [], series = [], rows = [];
    var wholeYears = Math.ceil(t);
    for (var y = 0; y <= wholeYears; y++) {
      var yr = Math.min(y, t);
      var v = p * Math.pow(1 + r / mFreq, mFreq * yr);
      labels.push('Y' + y); series.push(v);
      if (y > 0) rows.push([y, CM.inr(v - p), CM.inr(v)]);
    }
    CM.lineChart('chart-growth', labels, [{ label: 'Value', data: series, role: '--s1', fill: true }]);
    CM.table('sched-out', ['Year', 'Interest (cum.)', 'Value'], rows);
  }
  CM.bind(['p', 'r', 'n'], recalc);
});
</script>
